Variables in noir can be declared mutable via the mut keyword. Mutable variables can be reassigned to via an assignment expression. let x = 2;
x = 3; // error: x must be mutable to be assigned to let mut y = 3;
let y = 4; // OK The mut modifier can also apply to patterns: let (a, mut b) = (1, 2);
a = 11; // error: a must be mutable to be assigned to
b = 12; // OK let mut (c, d) = (3, 4);
c = 13; // OK
d = 14; // OK // etc.
let MyStruct { x: mut y } = MyStruct { x: a }
// y is now in scope Note that mutability in noir is local and everything is passed by value, so if a called function mutates its parameters then the parent function will keep the old value of the parameters. fn main() -> Field { let x = 3; helper(x); x // x is still 3
} fn helper(mut x: i32) { x = 4;
}

